Goal: Make the device-monitoring agent install itself silently with one click, and demo it through a real login + download flow

Add self-scheduling to the agent script — modify getinfo.py so that every time it runs, it sends a heartbeat immediately and registers itself in Windows Task Scheduler using a combined trigger: "at system startup" (runs under the SYSTEM account, independent of login state) plus a recurring "every 5 minutes" trigger (so it self-corrects if interrupted). This gets close to real Windows Service reliability without needing a full service implementation.
Convert the updated script into a standalone .exe — use PyInstaller (pyinstaller --onefile getinfo.py) so it runs on any Windows machine without needing Python installed.
Build a simple website with a login page — a basic page with one hardcoded username/password for the demo (not full multi-user authentication), just enough to demonstrate "log in first" as a concept.
Add a "Download Agent" button/page — after login, a page that serves up the .exe file for download.
Test the full flow on a clean/demo machine — log into the website, click download, run the .exe once, and confirm: the device immediately appears on the dashboard (first heartbeat), the scheduled task is visible in Task Scheduler, and it keeps sending heartbeats automatically afterward without running it again manually.
(Already partly done) Finish online/offline status logic — so the dashboard accurately reflects when a registered device stops sending heartbeats, which is what makes the "close the laptop / it goes offline" demo moment work.
For the actual interview demo — remove your own machine's existing entry from the database beforehand, then live-demo the real flow: log in on the website, download, run once, and show it appear on the manager dashboard in real time, including the online/offline transition.